Answer: There is no specific Java library for color detection in images. However, you can use Java Advanced Imaging (JAI) or JavaFX for image processing.

For JAI, you can use the Marvin Image Processing Library. It provides a variety of image processing algorithms, including color histogram generation.

For JavaFX, you can use the ColorHistogram class to generate a color histogram from an image, and then find the most common color.

Here is an example of how you can use ColorHistogram:

```java
import javafx.scene.image.Image;
import javafx.scene.image.PixelReader;
import javafx.scene.paint.Color;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Image image = new Image("path_to_your_image");
        PixelReader pixelReader = image.getPixelReader();

        int width = (int) image.getWidth();
        int height = (int) image.getHeight();

        int[] histogram = new int[256];

        for (int y = 0; y < height; y++) {
            for (int x = 0; x < width; x++) {
                Color color = pixelReader.getColor(x, y);
                int red = (int) (color.getRed() * 255);
                int green = (int) (color.getGreen() * 255);
                int blue = (int) (color.getBlue() * 255);

                int gray = (red + green + blue) / 3;
                histogram[gray]++;
            }
        }

        int max = 0;
        int mostCommonColor = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < histogram.length; i++) {
            if (histogram[i] > max) {
                max = histogram[i];
                mostCommonColor = i;
            }
        }

        System.out.println("Most common color: " + mostCommonColor);
    }
}
